{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_nipon_ver01/data/10021978/00271764832/1921020901/0107.xml":{"full_text":"THE FOUNDATION OF PROSPERITY.\nA great deal is being said these days about\nbusiness depression. That tbere is such a con\ndition no one will deny. There is difference of\nopinion as to the reason for this depression\nand also as to the length of time it will con\ntinue.\nA question that is uppermost in the minds\nof many is as to how this depression may be\novercome and business be brought back to nor\nmal conditions. Many suggestions have been\nmade, and many remedies have been proposed.\nSome say that wages must be reduced so as lo\nbring down the cost of production. Others\nsay wages must be maintained at present levels\nin order that the wage earner may be able to\nbuy liberally. Some say that the Government\nmust regulate business as to prices and ;n\nmany other ways. Others say that the trouble\nis that the Government has tried to do too\nmuch regulating, and that it ought to let busi\nness take eare of itself. Some say that the\nGovernment should finance certain lines of\nbusiness. Others say that this is entirely be\nyond the province of the Government. Some\nsay that what is needed is to develop foreign\ntrade, so that we can sell our products abroad.\nOthers want them sold at home.\nThere are just scores of other remedies p re\nposed by those who pose as doctors to the body\npolitic. An examination of these various pro\nposals will show that almost all of them have\nlittle or no value as a remedy for the existing\nbusiness depression.\nMr. Roger W. Babson, head of the Babson\nStatistical Organization, has been giving this\nsubject careful investigation, lie is reported\nto have said in a public address, \"that a period\nof depression is the result of unrighteousness,\ndishonesty, extravagance and inefficiency,\nwhich developed in the latter half of a period\nof prosperity; and secondly that a period >?f\nprosperity is the reaction from the righteous\nness, industry, integrity and thrift which de\nvelop in the latter half of a period of depres\nsion.\"\nIn trying to show the remedy for those ex\nisting conditions, he says:\n\"It is not railroads, steamships or factories\nwhich cause our prosperity; it is not bank\nclearings, foreign trade, or commodity prices,\nwhich give us good business. All these things\nare mere thermometers that register the tem\nperature of the room. Prosperity is based on\nthose fundamental qualities of faith, temper\nance, service and thrift, which are the pro\nducts of religion. The fundamentals of pros\nperity are the Ten Commandments.\"\nIt should be remembered that Mr. Babson is\nnot a preacher, but a practical business man,\nwhose work is to study conditions as they are,\nto discover their causes and where conditions\nneed to be changed to suggest remedies.\nMr. Babson further says on this subject:\n\"The future of American business depends on\nthe developing of the soul of the man and upon\nagain permeating labor, capital and manage\nment with integrity, loyalty and a desire to\nserve. The need of the hour is not more sales\nmen, or more foremen, or more technical men,\nbut the need of the hour is to get employers\nand wage earners to give their hearts to God.\nBusiness depressions can be avoided, but only\nby redirecting the minds of your people to the\nneed of integrity, industry and thrift. Busi\nness conditions can be changed for the better\nonly as man's attitude towards life changes.\"\nDoes not this offer to Christian business men\na suggestion that is most worthy of their con\nsideration? Every one who has ever made\nany investigation along this line knows that\nreligion develops prosperity. Start a mission\nchurch in a poor community and in a little\n?while evidences of increasing prosperity among\nthe people will be seen. Send missionaries\ninto a heathen country, and as soon as they\nare Avon to the Christian religion, they be\ncome more prosperous in temporal affairs. It\nhas often been said by those who are in a po\nsition to know that the business men of this\ncountry could well afford to finance all the for\neign mission work done by all the mission\nagencies of all the churches, for where relig\nion goes civilization is developed; and where\ncivilization is developed there grows, up a de\nmand for many things that were not known\nor needed before and there also follows the\ndevelopment of the ability to buy what will\nsupply the newly created needs.\nThe same principle holds true of the country\nat large. The principles of the religion of\nJesus Christ in the heart will produce industry,\nhonesty in labor, faithful service on the part\nof employer and employe, a just return for la\nbor performed, the careful and wise and eco\nnomical expenditure of the earnings of labor.\nThis means prosperity, which is the opposite\nof depression.\nDoes this not suggest the Presbyterian Pro\ngressive Program? Its great aim is to develop\nthe religious life and character of the indi\nvidual, to strengthen the Church, God's ap\npointed agent for the teaching and training of\nmen, women and children in the principle and\npractice of religion, and to spread the religion\nof Christ throughout the world.\nIf the business men and others of our Church\nwant to see depression banished from the land\nand prosperity take its place, let them for the\nnext, two months throw themselves heart and\nsoul into the Progressive Program.\n\"Seek ye first the kingdom of God and all\nthese things shall be added unto you.\"\nA UNIVERSAL GOSPEL.\nThe Gospel is not a method of reform. Its\nattack on social and political evils is indirect.\nIt seeks the cause and believes the disease will\ndisappear. It is not ai system of philosophy,\nhowever true it is that God is the Master Lo\ngician.\nNeither is the Gospel a social creed. It\nemphasizes the brotherhood of man, after it\nhas brought men into the adoption of children\nthrough faith in Jesus Christ. And when it lias\nthus emphasized this great truth, all social\ndemands will be satisfied.\nThe Gospel is a plan?of salvation. A way by\nwhich man can get himself into right rela\ntions with God. It is God's plan. This is\nso true that one of the names that Jesus chose\nfor Himself was \"The Way,\" and a common\nname of His disciples was \"those of the way.\"\nWe have been so much absorbed in the results\nof the gospel that we have often forgotten this\nsimple truth.\nHence it is absolutely indifferent to the cir\ncumstances and conditions of mankind. To it\nthere is no rich and poor, no cultured and un\ncultured, Jew nor Gentile. It treats man in his\nelementary and raw state. It rests upon plain\nand simple facts that pertain to all men. Man\nis a sinner, lost and helpless, everywhere. God\nis just and through the death of Jes.us Christ\nbecomes the justifier of them that believe.\nThere is a vast difference between the Hot\ntentot and the cultured European, but when\nit comes to salvation there is none whatever.\nThe gospel is the universal plan of salvation.\nThere is a universal need for the gospel. Go\nwhere you will you find the fact of sin. The\ntrail of the serpent is over us all. Various in\nform, different in degree of virulence, but indi\ncating the existence of a poison everywhere.\nGo where you will you find the consequences\nof sin, fear, distrust, hatred, selfishness, cru\nelty. Au eminent statesman has declared that\n\"there are not ten square miles of the earth's\nsurface unaffected by Christianity in which a\nman's life or a woman's honor would be safe\na day.\"\nThe Gospel is the final product of a univer\nsal God. lie has no other plan. Devised in\neternity it is executed in time. God is God of\nthe whole universe. \"The world is mine.\"\n\"All things were created by Ilim, and by Him\nthey exist.\"\nHeathenism localized its god. So did the\nJew, trying to make every man a Jew, that he\nmight become the heir of salvation, lint God\nis not limited by racial or national lines. He\nis \"the same Lord\" to all.\nThis Gospel is adapted to all men. In its\nsimplicity it is available to the lowest intel\nlects. It can be understood by the simplest\nmind, if that mind wishes to know it. Its\nfacts are elementary and belong to the pri\nmary grade.\nIts agent is the Holy Spirit who wills to\nenter and abide in the lowliest soul, in the\nchild innocent of overt acts of sin, or in old\n\"Born Drunk\" of the East Side of London.\nIt is adapted through its avenue of access.\n\"By faith ye are saved.\" Its avenue is simple\ntrust. Is there anything that would so win\nthe heart and rectify the relations as confi\ndence? It has accomplished wonders.\nThe only way in which I know that a rem\nedy will cure another is that I have seen it\ncure me or some other one afflicted in like\nmanner. Then I can assure the sick man that\nit will cure him.\nThe outstanding fact is that the Gospel has\nmade the Anglo-Saxon race what is is. There\nwere many other strains that entered into this\ncomposite race, we call the English in its broad\nsense, but all of them were heathen of the\ndeepest dye, worshipping Thor and Odin and\nsacrificing children and captives on their al\ntars, cruel and merciless and ignorant as any\ntribe of Africa.\nGod sent His missionaries and through the\nlong years it has worked until now we are\nstanding in the foremost files of time. We\nhave the light.\nThe Gospel has been and is the power of\nGod unto salvation to all that believe, whether\nJew or Gentile. It will be the power of God\nto the end of the Age. Then we ought to preach\nthat and that alone. I)o away with all the\nsocial and philosophic and reformative pana\nceas from our pulpits and in dealing with\nsinners, and proclaim the holy gospel of Jesus\nChrist. We ought to accept it Willi perfect\nconfidence as the hope of the heathen and\nwith all our might send it, as the only salva\ntion of man. A. A. L.\nContributed\nPREDESTINATION? FREE WILL.\nAn Attempted Adjustment.\nBy Rev. \"William H. Bates, D. D.\nThe question of God 's sovereignty in predes\ntination and man's free agency in action has\nbeen, if possible, even more than that of the\norigin of sin, the question of the ages. It pre\nsents a difficulty that all thoughtful persons\nmen, women and even children have strug\ngled with, almost always with distraction,\nvery, very seldom with anything of satisfac\ntion. The attempt is here made to bring some\nthing of satisfaction into a consideration of\nthis perplexing question.","height":"16815","width":"11643"}}
